          "body": "Verse 3 places two claims in immediate tension: 'The LORD is slow to anger and great in power, and the LORD will by no means leave the guilty unpunished.' Generations of readers have wanted to use the first clause to soften the third. Nahum refuses that reading. The verse does not say God is slow to anger because He is weak or indifferent, nor that His slowness means the guilty will finally go free. It says He is slow to anger and simultaneously great in power, and simultaneously will by no means leave the guilty unpunished. All three claims are simultaneous and non-negotiable.\n\nThis is the Old Testament's answer to every form of cheap-grace theology. The God who does not immediately execute judgment is not a God who has abandoned judgment; He is a God whose patience accumulates toward a more final and thorough reckoning. Nahum writes a century after Jonah's mission. Nineveh repented under Jonah's preaching (Jonah 3); God relented. A century later, Nineveh has returned to violence (Nahum 3:1-4), and the slowness of God's anger, which produced the reprieve of Jonah's day, has now run its course. The patience was real. The judgment is now equally real. Peter will draw the same theological logic in 2 Peter 3:9-10: the Lord is patient, not wishing for any to perish — but the day of the Lord will come."
