        "title": "Jealous, avenging, slow to anger — the non-negotiable fullness of divine character",
        "range": "1:2-3",
        "excerpt": "A jealous and avenging God is the Lord; the Lord is avenging and wrathful... The Lord is slow to anger and great in power, and the Lord will by no means leave the guilty unpunished.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a theological claim that will unsettle every reader who has domesticated God into a figure of benevolent tolerance. Three times in verse 2 the divine name stands as the subject of verbs of vengeance. The repetition is not rhetorical carelessness; it is liturgical insistence. Nahum will not allow the reader to hear 'avenging' as an attribute of some lesser deity; it belongs to the covenant LORD, the God of the Exodus and Sinai, the God who promised in Deuteronomy 32:35 that 'vengeance is Mine, and retribution.'\n\nThe descriptor 'jealous' (qanno) requires careful handling. Qanno in the Old Testament is the attribute declared at Sinai in Exodus 20:5 and 34:14 — the exclusive, zealous claim of a sovereign over what belongs to Him by covenant right. God is jealous for His own glory and for His covenant people. Nineveh has violated both: it has ravaged the people of the covenant (Nahum 3:19 describes the universal suffering Assyria inflicted), and it has attributed its victories to gods of wood and stone (2 Kings 18:33-35). The jealousy of God is therefore not a psychological defect but a moral claim: the injury done to what belongs to God demands a response from God.\n\nVerse 3 pairs two attributes that nervous readers have historically tried to play against each other. 'Slow to anger' is presented not as a softening of divine judgment but as its companion: the LORD is simultaneously slow to anger AND will by no means leave the guilty unpunished. His slowness is real — He waited a century after Jonah before acting on Nineveh. His certainty of judgment is equally real — when the patience concludes, the verdict is total. This is the pastoral logic of the whole chapter: what Judah in its exhaustion needed to hear was not that God had changed but that His patience toward Nineveh had a terminus, and the terminus had arrived.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qanno* (jealous) is used almost exclusively of God in the Old Testament — it is a divine attribute-word, not a common term for human jealousy. *Naqah* (leave unpunished) in the form *naqqeh lo' yenaqqeh* is a doubled Hebrew construction of the strongest possible negation: 'not clearing, He will not clear' — an absolute refusal to acquit the guilty. *Arekh aph* (slow to anger) is literally 'long of nose' — the Hebrew idiom pictures the nostrils flaring slowly with breath rather than instantly with rage."
