        "number": 2,
        "title": "Creation unmade — the theophany establishes the scale of divine sovereignty",
        "range": "1:3b-6",
        "excerpt": "In whirlwind and storm is His way, and clouds are the dust beneath His feet... Who can stand before His indignation? Who can endure the burning of His anger?",
        "body": "The hymn's center section (vv.3b-6) is a theophany — a description of the LORD's appearance in power that draws on the canonical tradition of divine self-revelation in storm (Exodus 19:16-19; Psalm 18:7-15; Habakkuk 3:3-15). Nahum deploys the tradition with unmistakable intention: before the reader hears a word about Nineveh's fate, they must stand before the God who is coming in that fate. The theophanic images are arranged in descending scale: atmosphere (whirlwind, storm, clouds), hydrosphere (sea dried, rivers emptied), biosphere (Bashan, Carmel, Lebanon withered), geosphere (mountains quake, hills dissolve), and finally the entire inhabited world (v.5).\n\nThe compression of the greatest natural powers under the LORD's feet is rhetorically devastating for any imperial claim. Assyrian royal ideology built its propaganda on the image of the king as the embodiment of divine power, the one who made rivers run, who caused lands to wither and flourish at his command. Nahum takes every one of those imperial images and applies them to the LORD alone. Clouds are dust beneath His feet — the highest atmospheric phenomenon is pavement. Bashan, Carmel, and Lebanon — the most fertile, most beautiful, most resource-rich territories in the ancient Levant — wither at His presence. Mountains, the ancient world's ultimate symbol of permanence and stability, dissolve like wax (Micah 1:4 uses the same image). Nineveh's walls and armies, however impressive, are being measured against the One who dissolves mountains.\n\nVerse 6's rhetorical questions — 'Who can stand before His indignation? Who can endure the burning of His anger?' — are designed to produce the correct answer: no one. Not Israel's enemies in Egypt (Exodus 9:11), not the Canaanite nations, not Babylon, not Assyria. The questions set up the chapter's central pastoral move in verse 7: when the answer is 'no one can stand before His indignation,' the news that there is a stronghold, a refuge, a place of knowing and being known by this God, is not merely comforting — it is staggering.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Suphah* (whirlwind) and *searah* (storm) appear together in Job 38:1 and Zechariah 9:14 in theophanic contexts. *Gaar* (rebuke, v.4) is the same verb used in Psalm 106:9 of God rebuking the Red Sea at the Exodus — Nahum is consciously invoking the Exodus tradition. *Chemah* (wrath, v.6) — burning heat — is the most intense Hebrew word for anger, used of God in Deuteronomy 29:28 to describe the wrath that resulted in exile."
