        "body": "The transition from verse 6 to verse 7 is one of the most dramatic turns in prophetic literature. Verse 6 ends with a rhetorical question that demands the answer 'no one': who can endure the burning of His anger? Verse 7 responds not by qualifying the anger but by naming a different category of person relative to that God: those who take refuge in Him. The LORD is good — the same LORD who is avenging and wrathful (v.2), who dries up seas and dissolves mountains (vv.4-5), whose wrath is poured out like fire and breaks rocks (v.6). 'Good' here is not a tonal softening but a fuller disclosure: this God is morally excellent, covenantally faithful, and actively beneficent toward those who flee to Him.\n\nThe word 'stronghold' (maoz) is military — a fortified position that holds in the day of siege. The 'day of trouble' is precisely the situation of Judah under Assyrian domination: the siege of Jerusalem under Sennacherib (701 BC) was within living memory for Nahum's audience. The nation had watched 185,000 Assyrian soldiers die overnight at the angel of the LORD's hand (2 Kings 19:35). Verse 7 addresses a people who knew experientially that the LORD was a stronghold in the day of trouble — and who also lived with the daily grind of continuing Assyrian tribute and political humiliation.\n\nThe final clause — 'He knows those who take refuge in Him' — is the deepest pastoral comfort in the chapter. 'Knows' (yada) in Hebrew covenant usage is not mere cognitive awareness. It is the relational knowledge of a covenant partner — the word used of God's knowing Israel in Amos 3:2 ('You only have I known of all the families of the earth'), of the LORD knowing Moses 'face to face' (Deuteronomy 34:10). To be known by this God is to be in the covenant, in the protection, in the refuge. Nahum is not offering general religious comfort; he is making a specific claim: the terrifying God of the theophanic hymn has specific, personal, covenantal knowledge of those who trust Him, and that knowledge is their safety.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maoz* (stronghold) appears in Psalm 27:1 ('the LORD is my light and my salvation... my stronghold') — the Psalter echoes confirm this is established covenant vocabulary. *Yada* (knows) — covenantal knowledge, not merely cognitive recognition; the same verb used of God's 'knowing' the affliction of Israel in Egypt (Exodus 3:7). *Chasah* (take refuge) — to flee for shelter, to trust as a place of safety; the root of the Hebrew word for the wing-shelter of God (Psalm 91:4)."
