        "title": "Liberation promised, gospel announced — the oracle to Judah",
        "range": "1:12-15",
        "excerpt": "So now, I will break his yoke bar from upon you, and I will tear off your shackles... Behold, on the mountains the feet of him who brings good news, who announces peace!",
        "body": "The oracle's final movement addresses Judah directly, alternating between Nineveh's doom (v.14) and Judah's liberation (vv.12-13, 15). The divine speech of verses 12-13 acknowledges something pastorally stunning: 'Though I have afflicted you, I will afflict you no longer.' The affliction Judah suffered under Assyrian domination — the tribute, the humiliation, the deportations — was not merely Assyrian cruelty. It was the LORD's own hand at work in providential discipline (cf. Isaiah 10:5, where Assyria is called 'the rod of My anger'). Nahum does not suppress this uncomfortable truth; he names it and then reverses it. The instrument of affliction will be broken off the afflicted.\n\nThe yoke-and-shackle imagery of verse 13 is Exodus-saturated. The breaking of the yoke bar (mot) and the tearing of shackles (moser) echo the language of Israel's liberation from Egypt — indeed, the very vocabulary of Leviticus 26:13 ('I broke the bars of your yoke and made you walk erect'). Nahum is proclaiming a new exodus for Judah. The oppressor who replaced Pharaoh will himself be broken by the same LORD who shattered Pharaoh's army at the Red Sea. The redemption-pattern of Scripture is recurring: every Pharaoh, every Sennacherib, every Nineveh falls before the LORD who hears the cry of the afflicted.\n\nVerse 15 is the chapter's doxological conclusion and its most theologically resonant verse. The image of the herald whose feet are on the mountains bringing good news of peace is quoted almost verbatim in Isaiah 52:7, which Paul applies to gospel preachers in Romans 10:15. Nahum's messenger announces the peace that comes from the destruction of Nineveh; Isaiah's messenger announces the peace that comes from the Servant's suffering; Paul's messenger announces the peace that comes from Christ's cross and resurrection. The herald-image moves typologically from the historical liberation of 612 BC to the eschatological liberation of the gospel. Judah is commanded to celebrate feasts and pay vows — not after the fall of Nineveh, but now, in advance, on the basis of the divine word that has already settled Nineveh's fate. This is the structure of biblical faith: acting in the present on the certainty of a future that God has declared.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Basar* (brings good news, v.15) — the same root as the New Testament's *euangelion* in its Hebrew background; Isaiah 52:7, 61:1, and Nahum 1:15 share this vocabulary. *Shalom* (peace) — the comprehensive well-being that comes when right relationship with God is restored and the enemy of that relationship is removed. *Chagag* (celebrate your feasts) — to keep the pilgrimage festivals; the command to celebrate anticipates completed deliverance while it is still future, requiring faith to obey. *Neder* (vows) — fulfilling vows was the prescribed liturgical response to answered prayer (cf. Psalm 22:25; Jonah 2:9)."
